<|begin_of_text|>The Arlington County Board plans to vote Saturday afternoon on giving Amazon $23 million and other incentives to build a headquarters campus in Crystal City, but only after hearing scores of northern Virginia residents and advocates testify for or against the project.
The five-member board held public hearings first during its regular meeting Friday morning, and then at a special meeting Friday afternoon. The spectacle lasted more than nine hours and included close to 500 speakers, all calling out against the project or supporting the plans to lease the county’s land in Crystal City to Amazon for $23 million. But speakers also listed an array of suggestions for adding accountability measures to the planned incentives and limiting the scope of the impact that Amazon’s move could have on affordable housing in the area.
The board begins voting at its next meeting scheduled for 1 p.m. on Saturday.
“I understand the role of this board is to oversee the interests of the county, but as a resident of Potomacture and a grandmother of two children who look to Crystal City as their playground— myself, can’t help but be a little worried about what Crystal City is about to become,” said resident Maria Fama.
Others warned that the arrival of the tech giant would mean the loss of affordable housing and open space for community gathering.
Erick Walters, a member of the youth-led Coalition for Resilient Crystal City, said: “There are literally chances that the county could now be sitting here planning for a cemetery.”
Some of the speakers urged the county board members to put a cap on what restrictions can be applied to the county’s deed restrictions—which limit the development of Amazon’s leasehold interest—to mitigate the adverse impacts that the company’s arrival could have on the community.

During an appearance on CNN, Frieden noted that three people had tested negative for the disease so far, but the results could be incomplete.
"Most patients show some sort of symptoms between three and 21 days, so we have 21 days on the clock as there are other colleagues who have at least some of the symptoms," Frieden said.

Of those, 48 received proper protective equipment including gowns, gloves and face masks, and the CDC said it came into contact with 38 of those 48.
Of the 38, two people are being tested and the results came back negative, Frieden said.
"They are focusing around some block parties that several of these other colleagues attended," he said during an appearance CBS's "Face the Nation." "In Dallas, the two other people that tested negative, there were a couple of block parties that they went to that some of the others attended.
"Neither of those — so far — has any symptoms, but that group includes five to 10 people who could be in the contagious window."
The five people who were exposed to Duncan but not wearing proper protective equipment have declined to be tested, Frieden said.

With its new management, PDS hopes to be profitable in the short term albeit its balance sheet still requires a recapitalization.
The main objective of the PDS transfer, which is expected to be finalized in the next few weeks, is to bring down the quasi capital of the PSE – locally called Quasi Leonza – to the required level of P200 million.

Angelo “Andy” Douglas Azzato, 47, of Lucerne Valley, was found at about 9:30 a.m. in the eastbound lanes of Old Woman Springs Road east of Cypress Street, close to the San Bernardino County line, said Cal Fire Battalion Chief Rob Fuemmeler.
Azzato’s bicycle was on the westbound side of the road, Fuemmeler said.
A 911 caller reported around 8:40 a.m. finding someone on the ground in Old Woman Springs Road, according to a spokesperson with California Highway Patrol dispatch.
It is not clear if the victim was struck by the same car that hit and clipped Doug Azzato, 56, a resident of the Valley of Enchantment, who called 911ture after a driver cut into his lane, sending him over his handlebars.
Douglas Azzato spotted his brother laying unconscious in the road and ran over to him to look for injuries.
Doug Azzato limped along the road and stopped a motorist to report the incident and provide a description of the car to the person reporting it for the CHP.
“I got there at 9:42 p.m.,” Lt. Crocker of the Barstow CHP told the Daily Press. “It was a dark-colored four-door sedan that almost hit Doug Azzato. We received the call at 9 p.m. and the driver was either coming from Barstow or Amboy, clear over towards the county line. The description we received was a male, early 20’s to early 30’s with blonde hair and jeans. We do not have any suspect information at this time.”
Doug Azzato sustained “possible” injuries requiring hospital treatment, Crocker said, but made it home shortly after deciding to make the call to authorities.
“He made the call because he was unsure if others would find his brother,” Crocker said. “It’s a sense of community to use your cell phone now, especially in isolated areas.”

Azzato’s bicycle was on the westbound side of the road, Fuemmeler said.
A 911 caller reported around 8:40 a.m. finding someone on the ground in Old Woman Springs Road, according to a spokesperson with California Highway Patrol dispatch.

Douglas Azzato spotted his brother laying unconscious in the road and ran over to him to look for injuries.
Doug Azzato limped along the road and stopped a motorist to report the incident and provide a description of the car to the person reporting it for the CHP.
“I got there at 9:42 p.m.,” Lt. Crocker of the Barstow CHP told the Daily Press. “It was a dark-colored four-door sedan that almost hit Doug Azzato. <|begin_of_text|>Unprecedented back-to-back annual coral bleaching events have affected two-thirds of the Great Barrier Reef, with this year's event already leading to mortality of half the corals in some key tourist tracts, scientists say.
Record-breaking warm waters along Australia's northeast coast during 2014-15 laid waste to some sections of the reef, with the spectacle Australia's worst ever mass bleaching event.
In this year's first major climate-related event to blight the reef, ocean temperatures have again climbed toward record highs, leaving coral communities across the Great Barrier Reef extremely susceptible to a repeat.
Coral bleaching happens when fragile polyps -- the microscopic animals that form the building blocks of coral colonies -- abandon their symbiotic relationship with microscopic algae called zooxanthellae.
The switch occurs when algae are expelled due to the buildup of stress hormones in the coral tissue, often a symptom of rising seawater temperatures.
The next phase of bleture is a pale or bleached appearance -- hence the name -- irrespective of the light level within the water.
While a historic back-to-back bleaching event is the worst case scenario, temperatures are warm enough to bring about a second bout of bleaching and other related stress responses.
Temperatures along the Queensland coast have attained the highest on record for the first five months of the calendar year, ending extremely close to going into the danger zone for widespread bleaching.
Recently, temperatures peaked at record levels in the northern Keppel waterhouses, which hosts the Great Barrier Reef's southernmost coral communities. The current event is already causing coral stress and mortality in this region.
In the iconic southern Whitsundays region, coral stress and bleaching conditions continue and there is some early mortality to northern acropora, which is expected to escalate downstream.
Further south in the Capricorn-Bunker zone, coral stress conditions persist across the boundary for Coral Sea waters, and early thermally-induced mortality has been detected.
